sec.p:
Morphology, dissections and terminology. The total length of a specimen was measured in lateral view by summing the distances from the frons (antenna excluded) to the scutellum apex and from the scutellum apex to the abdomen apex. To study the internal morphology of the male terminalia, the abdomen apex was cut off at the third tergite, placed into lactic acid (85%), and heated at 150°C over a Thermo Scientific Cimarec plate for approximately 25 minutes (
). The pieces were dissected and photographed in glycerin using a concave slide. After study, genitalia were stored in microvials containing glycerin. The wings were mounted on microslides with Canada balsam. The microvial and microslide were pinned along with the respective specimen. The external morphological terminology follows
. The following abbreviations were used: a : anterior surface, ad : anterodorsal surface, av : anteroventral surface, cerc : cercus, d : dorsal surface, distph : distiphallus, epand : epandrium, epiph : epiphallus, epiprct : epiproct, hypd : hypandrium, hyprct : hypoproct, p : posterior surface, pd : posterodorsal surface, pgt : postgonite, phapod : phallapodeme, pregt : pregonite, pv : posteroventral surface, st : sternite, sur : surstylus, tg : tergite, and v : ventral surface.

Images and map.
Photographs were taken with a Leica digital camera DFC450 coupled to a stereomicroscope Leica M205A and connected to a computer with Leica Application Suite software, with automatic mounting module (synchronization software) (http://www.syncroscopy.com/syncroscopy/). Microphotograph of the antenna were taken with a Hitachi scanning electron microscope TM4000 II. Illustrations of the terminalia were made using Infinite Painter software, using the corresponding digital images. The map showing geographic records of the two species was plotted using the SimpleMappr software (

).

